    <section class="about section-headless section-bg">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="row">
                <h3>Physical Health Check-up</h3>
                <p class="fst-italic" style="text-align: justify">
                    As part of our commitment to prioritize your well-being and the safety of the blood supply, a thorough physical health check-up will be conducted before the donation process. A qualified doctor will assess your overall health by asking you a series of questions related to your medical history. This information helps us ensure that you meet the necessary criteria for blood donation and that the process is safe for both you and the recipient. In addition, your blood pressure and hemoglobin level will be measured to further evaluate your suitability for donation. This comprehensive health evaluation is an essential step in safeguarding the well-being of both donors and recipients, ensuring that every blood donation is a responsible and beneficial act.
                </p>
                <br/>
                <h3>Blood Donation</h3>
                <p class="fst-italic" style="text-align: justify">
                    Once you have completed the registration and health check-up process, we will proceed with the blood donation itself. Our highly trained medical staff will prepare the donation site by cleansing an area on your arm with an antiseptic solution. They will then gently insert a brand new sterile needle for the blood draw. Rest assured that our team follows strict safety protocols to ensure a hygienic and comfortable experience for you.
                    <br/>
                    During the donation, which typically lasts about 8-10 minutes, you will be comfortably seated. The process itself is relatively painless, with most donors describing it as a quick pinch that subsides within seconds. Our skilled staff will carefully collect a unit of blood, typically ranging from 350 to 450 milliliters, which constitutes a complete donation.
                    <br/>
                    After the blood has been successfully collected, a staff member will promptly place a bandage on your arm to ensure proper healing and protection. This final step signifies the completion of your donation and serves as a visual reminder of the invaluable contribution you have made to saving lives.
                    <br/>
                </p>
                <br/>
                <br/>
                <h3>Safety</h3>
                <p class="fst-italic" style="text-align: justify">
                    Ensuring the safety of our donors is our utmost priority throughout the blood donation process. We maintain strict adherence to sterile practices, and all equipment used, including needles, is disposable and used only once before being safely discarded. This guarantees a clean and hygienic environment for every donation.
                    <br/>
                    It's important to note that donating 450 milliliters of blood, which is the standard amount for a donation, accounts for less than 10% of your total body volume in the majority of individuals. This means that the amount of blood collected is well within a safe limit. As a result, you can safely donate blood every 3 months without any adverse effects on your overall health.
                    <br/>
                    It's worth mentioning that your body continuously discards and replenishes blood, regardless of whether you donate or not. The amount donated during each session is quickly replenished by your body's natural processes. This ensures that your overall blood supply remains stable and balanced, allowing you to donate regularly without any concerns.
                    <br/>
                    <br/>
                </p>
            </div>
